1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
 Jeff Gotlieb:

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:12,000
 Okay. Hello everyone. My name is Jeff Gotlieb. I'm with the International Monetary Fund.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:21,000
 I'm the IMF's res rep for Central and Eastern Europe, based in Warsaw, and I cover Central and Eastern Europe out of Warsaw.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:27,000
 It's great to be here, and thank you very much to the Croatian National Bank for the invitation.

5
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:33,000
 The only thing more amazing than the beauty of Dubrovnik is how much of Croatia actually looks like this.

6
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:40,000
 It's really not a one-stop, one-trick pony, and it's a good reason to keep Croatians close to you in life.

7
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:47,000
 It's really great to be here, and I think labor is an excellent time to discuss the labor issue.

8
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:56,000
 As many of you know, there were two main ways that much of the profession got the inflation thing wrong.

9
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:02,000
 The first one was to not expect inflation to be such a problem in the first place.

10
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:07,000
 The second one was that even if you did think that there was too much demand and it was going to come to inflation,

11
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:14,000
 many people thought that it would come through wages and tension in the labor market, not through goods, which is what we've seen.

12
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:23,000
 So thus far, the labor market has not been the key player in the inflation process, but now it seems like things are turning.

13
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:28,000
 So the initial shock has started to fade in terms of the components.

14
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:30,000
 The labor market is still very tight.

15
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
 Core inflation is very high.

16
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:41,000
 So when I talk to policymakers, most of them seem to agree that to the degree they get inflation wrong going forward,

17
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:45,000
 it might be because they're misestimating what is happening in the labor market.

18
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:52,000
 So just to frame the discussion for my colleagues here today, I'll just briefly touch on three questions.

19
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,000
 Where are we now and why?

20
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:56,000
 Where are we going?

21
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,000
 And what should policymakers do about it?

22
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:08,000
 So on the first, when we talk about labor market resilience, we're usually talking about the quantity side, basically employment.

23
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,000
 And there's two parts of this story.

24
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:17,000
 The first is the vacancy unemployment story, where we basically saw a shift up in the beverage curve.

25
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:22,000
 People have different reasons for this, from matching to people leaving the labor force.

26
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:29,000
 But this is the key reason that people think the unemployment rate understates the true tightness in the labor market.

27
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:38,000
 The second, which is a bit less discussed, is that employment growth is actually positive in many of the major and emerging market economies.

28
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:45,000
 So it's not a story where employment is falling, but slowly, or employment is steady and there's hoarding.

29
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 We have a situation where even with falling output, we have firms adding employees.

30
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,000
 So you see a fall in labor productivity.

31
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:00,000
 You can come up with a variety of stories for this, but labor productivity growth in many countries is negative,

32
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:02,000
 depending exactly on how you measure it.

33
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:06,000
 So well below trend, and surprisingly so.

34
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:07,000
 It can't be sustained.

35
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:12,000
 Either you would expect output to start to recover, or employment to fall.

36
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:17,000
 But now moving on to the price side, wages.

37
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:20,000
 Wages, as I said, have not been a big player.

38
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:23,000
 You wouldn't describe them as wildly resilient.

39
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:30,000
 So as many people have cited, in advanced economies, real wages are negative.

40
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:36,000
 In emerging markets, they're a bit closer to even, but they have turned negative in the last two quarters.

41
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:45,000
 And so you have an inflation process where, consistent with maybe what you would expect, prices have been far more flexible than wages.

42
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 So if you decompose inflation thus far, you see a big increase in imported prices.

43
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:04,000
 You see a big increase in markups by firms, and that has led to the inflation, while real wages have remained negative to flat, resulting in high corporate profits.

44
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:08,000
 So again, this resilience story, I think one needs to separate.

45
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:19,000
 And depending on the country, in some cases the employment story I talked about has overwhelmed the negative real wage story, keeping demand overall strong.

46
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:25,000
 But again, I think it's important to separate these two, and I'll come back to that on the policy recommendation side.

47
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:28,000
 Okay, the second part is where we go from here.

48
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:31,000
 And there's kind of two broad stories.

49
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:41,000
 There's a benign scenario, which is where this vacancy unemployment rate issue solves itself, in kind of a soft landing respect.

50
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:50,000
 Which is basically that, rather than the vacancy unemployment ratio reflecting a deep matching problem, that might need a big increase in unemployment to solve.

51
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:57,000
 You basically have people come back to the labor force, and vacancies come down, without a rise in the unemployment rate.

52
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:00,000
 And so you get less concerned about the tightness of the labor market.

53
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 The second component is that you do get some increase in unemployment.

54
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:12,000
 So basically, you have weaker pricing power by firms consistent with the slowing economy.

55
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:14,000
 You get rising real wages.

56
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:17,000
 These two components drive profits down.

57
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
 And eventually, you see some uptick in unemployment.

58
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:30,000
 So if you got these two components, basically a fall in the vacancy unemployment ratio, some increase in unemployment because of the slowing economy and profit margins.

59
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:37,000
 Combined with no new shocks, that would be an environment in which I think we would all feel more comfortable about the inflation pressures.

60
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 But then there's also a significantly -- there's a less benign scenario, basically.

61
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:48,000
 I mean, one is that our star, to reference the previous presentation, is different from where we thought.

62
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:51,000
 So monetary policy is not as tight as we thought.

63
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:54,000
 The credit cycle turns.

64
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:57,000
 Pricing power is weaker than what we thought.

65
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:06,000
 Basically, profits stay somewhat high, and you're able to pass on higher prices, and inflation stays much stronger.

66
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:10,000
 At the same time, perhaps, we're exposed to new shocks.

67
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:18,000
 And it's -- there's obviously other scenarios, but these are kind of a benign and a much less benign scenario for where we go from here.

68
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:24,000
 But I think there's -- there's lots of questions in between those two scenarios.

69
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:31,000
 So just one last comment on -- in terms of what this all means for policymakers.

70
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:39,000
 I think outside of the profession and conferences like this, the framing about the labor market is not about resilience.

71
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:43,000
 So in the newspaper, it would be framed far more negatively.

72
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 It would be framed as a cost of living crisis, combined with extremely high corporate profits.

73
00:06:49,000 --> 00:07:00,000
 And I think that this angle, rather than the more positive angle of labor market resilience, is very important to consider for two reasons.

74
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:06,000
 One, on its own front, I think we need to be aware of the distributional consequences.

75
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:13,000
 There is the temporary issues of cost of living, and there's the more structural issue of the labor share of income.

76
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:19,000
 And I think that this is a fair angle that policymakers should be considering.

77
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:34,000
 The second is a bit more pernicious, which is that -- and I've had this in conversations with policymakers so far -- it's possible to take that diagnosis and get to policies that, at least we would think, are far more dangerous.

78
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:46,000
 Which is that the angle can be put that this is not something for monetary policy to do, but it's something for finance ministries and regulators to attack profits directly.

79
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:55,000
 And this can lead to consequences that ultimately don't address the underlying inflation problem while still compromising the fiscal.

80
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:05,000
 So we can maybe come back to some of those issues, but I think that this framing, both the macroeconomic, how much tightness do we need to address the inflation problem,

81
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:14,000
 and the more distributional issue of how we make sure that labor is supported over the course of this crisis, is important to consider.

82
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 So I will stop there and pass to our first speaker, Christian Kopp.

83
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:25,000
 Christian Kopp: Yes, thanks very much.

84
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 Great honor to be invited again to Dubrovnik.

85
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:41,000
 So I have -- I'm going to follow the agenda that Joff laid out, and start out with where are we now, and then have three thoughts on where we're going,

86
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:44,000
 and then maybe just one thought on what to do.

87
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,000
 So where are we now?

88
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:52,000
 I think the resilience of the labor market, first thought, has something to do with the strength of the service economy.

89
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:58,000
 And you can see that here in the picture from the beautiful dinner we had last night.

90
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:03,000
 That is one of the reasons why we have such a resilient and strong labor market.

91
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:08,000
 Now, in the short run, it is true that the labor market is surprisingly strong.

92
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:14,000
 We just heard in the previous presentation that we had a 200 basis point shock to real interest rates in most advanced economies.

93
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:26,000
 And I think most in the room, including myself, would not have expected such a resilient labor market in the face of that up drift in real interest rates.

94
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:33,000
 So we have in the U.S. an unemployment rate of 3.4 percent, which is the lowest level since 1969.

95
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:38,000
 And in the Euro area, we have an unemployment rate of 8.5 percent, which is the lowest level on record.

96
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 Even if you go back to the pre-Euro area period, we haven't had an 8.5 percent unemployment rate, I believe, probably since the 1950s or '60s.

97
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:51,000
 So it's a very resilient labor market.

98
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:59,000
 And if you look at the U.S., the early indicators on the labor market are not really pointing to a rapid decline in employment growth.

99
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:05,000
 We still have a lot of job openings, a lot of positions which companies are unable to fill.

100
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:10,000
 So then on the short run, two more thoughts.

101
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:14,000
 I think there is an element of labor hoarding, especially in the United States.

102
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:25,000
 So what I'm plotting here is the change in the private sector employment and the final sales to domestic consumers in constant prices.

103
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:33,000
 And you can see that the growth rate of the final sales to domestic consumers is much higher than the employment growth on trend.

104
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:37,000
 And that is indicative of labor productivity growth.

105
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:39,000
 But you don't have that since the pandemic.

106
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:43,000
 So index that back to December 2019.

107
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:48,000
 We can see that both time series are growing to the same extent.

108
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:57,000
 So that could be indicative of labor hoarding because, you know, I'd be surprised if productivity growth had suddenly fallen to zero.

109
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:04,000
 So I think that there is an element here of U.S. companies being unable to find the workers they need in the market.

110
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:11,000
 And therefore they are deciding to hold on to those workers because they feel that they were not able to find them again if they fire them now.

111
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:13,000
 Now that may at one point in time unravel.

112
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:21,000
 And there is a risk that if we do see a continuation of very weak domestic sales growth in the U.S.

113
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:26,000
 At one point in time, all of those U.S. companies at the same time start to, you know, fire people.

114
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:27,000
 And then that could backfire.

115
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:30,000
 But for the time being, there is some labor hoarding here.

116
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:36,000
 And I hope that the economy will recover and companies can hold on to the people they have.

117
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:42,000
 Now for the euro area, I don't think that we have an overheating labor market.

118
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:46,000
 These are two charts that I borrowed from Robin Brooks at the IAF.

119
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:55,000
 And you can see on the left-hand side the changes in core prices versus the changes in wages.

120
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:04,000
 And you can see that in most countries wage inflation is lower than core inflation in the euro area with the exception of Belgium and Greece for whatever reason.

121
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:06,000
 So we really don't have a wage price spiral here.

122
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 I think core inflation in the euro area is driven by other factors, probably by profit inflation, but not so much by wage inflation.

123
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:23,000
 And then another reason why I don't really think that we're facing an overheating EU labor market has to do with the labor force participation rates.

124
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:32,000
 And you can see that the employment to population ratio in most countries in the euro area is still below the previous peak, which was achieved in 2007.

125
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:39,000
 So I don't really think that we have an overheating labor market here, with a few exceptions.

126
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:41,000
 Maybe in Germany we have an element of that.

127
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:47,000
 But most other countries still have scope to increase the employment ratios.

128
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:49,000
 Now that's the short run.

129
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:56,000
 And the long run, here I would like to borrow an analysis that Daniel Gross has just presented, has just published.

130
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:02,000
 And that looks at the structural changes in the labor force participation rate.

131
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:06,000
 And what Daniel has done here, he's here in the room, and he'll speak later on.

132
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:15,000
 What Daniel has done here is he has attributed or he has related those changes in employment to changes in the education level.

133
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:22,000
 And it turns out that population cohorts with high levels of inflation tend to have a high level of education.

134
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:30,000
 And the increase in the educational achievement levels can explain around two-thirds of the increase in the EU labor force participation rate.

135
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:45,000
 So I think that the increase in employment, basically, you know, it's not that we had a lot of idle people before, especially women who were not part of the labor market.

136
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:49,000
 But what we're talking about here is labor market.

137
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:58,000
 So once you enter into, you know, into the division of labor, into formal employment, you need to have some form of specialization.

138
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:01,000
 If you do reproductive work at home, you're not idle.

139
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:07,000
 You do a lot of different things, you know, childcare, looking after whatever, you know, things in the household.

140
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:17,000
 But in order to become part of the formal labor market, I think you need some form of formal education in order to be able to contribute to this division of labor.

141
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:21,000
 And we see that the levels of formal education are rising rapidly in the EU area.

142
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:25,000
 And the consequence of that, we also see an increase in the employment to population ratio.

143
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:33,000
 So the longer run trend of the resilience of the labor market has to do with the fact that with the increase in education levels,

144
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:37,000
 with the participation in the labor market increases on trend.

145
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:40,000
 And that, I think, is something that will continue.

146
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:48,000
 The second point is related to the fact that we face very different patterns in different countries.

147
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:53,000
 So I've picked out three countries here, Hungary, Czech Republic, and Germany.

148
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:56,000
 And you can see that each one of those countries has very different patterns.

149
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:02,000
 You know, in Hungary and in the Czech Republic, we had a decline in employment in the years,

150
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:09,000
 following, you know, the end of communism because of the economic transformation.

151
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:14,000
 And that, in the beginning, led to negative employment and growth.

152
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:18,000
 What also happened is that in Hungary, at least, we had negative employment growth --

153
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:23,000
 sorry, negative labor force growth because we had a lot of outbound migration from Hungary.

154
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:27,000
 Now, Czech Republic is one of the countries that stands out for not having had that outbound migration.

155
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:32,000
 But I think in most CE countries -- I'll show that in the following slide -- we had that outbound migration,

156
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:36,000
 which is a big contributor to the tightness in the labor market.

157
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:48,000
 And then from 2000 -- you know, I suppose from 2010 onwards, we've had this rapid increase in employment in all Central European countries,

158
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:53,000
 which to some extent was export-driven, you know, so you have a very rapid increase there.

159
00:15:53,000 --> 00:16:03,000
 And that now leads to a situation where we have relatively tight labor markets in Central and Eastern Europe and the need to attract an inflow of migrant workers,

160
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:09,000
 which is something that we discussed here yesterday and which leads to problems in many of those countries.

161
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:11,000
 Now, Poland has had it easier.

162
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:15,000
 They've been able to attract people from Ukraine and Belarus even before the crisis.

163
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:20,000
 Other countries, such as Hungary, are having a tougher time increasing the labor force.

164
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:26,000
 And that has to do with some of the things we discussed -- which Joel Mocker discussed here yesterday,

165
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:36,000
 that he said phenotypical differences can lead to -- how did he put it -- there was a word that he used.

166
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:41,000
 It was not racism, yeah, but it was -- homophilia.

167
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:42,000
 Homophilia was the word.

168
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:43,000
 Yeah, exactly.

169
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:50,000
 So I think some of the countries find it difficult to attract and to, you know, integrate foreign workers.

170
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:52,000
 And Hungary is a case in point.

171
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:55,000
 And as a result of that, you have a very tight labor market in some of those countries.

172
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:02,000
 Other countries have been more open to migrant flows, and that has helped to mitigate the tightness in the labor market.

173
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:08,000
 Now, in Germany, you see a very strong rise in employment from 2005 onwards.

174
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:10,000
 And that was not related to migration.

175
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:14,000
 It was not related to economic transformation, but to a policy change.

176
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:18,000
 The HALS reforms were implemented in September 2003.

177
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:24,000
 And then from 2005 onwards, we've seen a rapid increase in employment because unemployment benefits were cut dramatically.

178
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:31,000
 by the German government, and that, you know, that contributed to this decline in the unemployment rate and also the rise in employment.

179
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:36,000
 So I think that, you know, the resilience of the labor market is a global phenomenon.

180
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:43,000
 Most of it can be attributed in advanced economies by structural changes, such as the increase in education achievements.

181
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:52,000
 And then within the individual countries, you have a lot of diversity, and the diversity is related to policy changes, such as, you know, labor market reforms.

182
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:59,000
 And also to, you know, the attitude towards migrant workers, which really differs from country to country.

183
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:09,000
 And here, there's another chart which shows the outbound migration, which has had a massive impact, especially in Eastern European countries.

184
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:15,000
 The chart that I borrowed from an analysis published by George Safari a couple of years ago.

185
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:27,000
 And you can see the, you know, the big outflows that all of those Central European countries have seen, both as a share of their labor force and as a share of the economically active population.

186
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:31,000
 In Romania, it was dramatic, you know, the outflux of people.

187
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:41,000
 And the Czech Republic stands out as one of the few countries which hasn't had much of an outflow of workers following the fall of the communist regime, you know.

188
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:46,000
 So really, there seem to be big differences in the individual countries.

189
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:48,000
 Final point on where we are going.

190
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:58,000
 So the first point is that we have a structural increase in education, which is one of the reasons why we have a very resilient labor market and growing labor force participation.

191
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:08,000
 Second point is the diversity that we have in the different countries, which is related to policy choices and unemployment benefits and to migration flows.

192
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:11,000
 And the third point is a little bit looking forward.

193
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:22,000
 And that has, that's just a question, whether we are at the threshold of a new area of very strong productivity growth driven by the increased use of artificial intelligence.

194
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:42,000
 Just, you know, an anecdote, I read a report recently that programmers at Microsoft have seen an increase in the productivity of their work by 50% through the use of large language models such as, you know, the ones that have been popularized now in a very short period of time.

195
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:50,000
 So, you know, the coding has become much faster for them and the debugging is now done by those artificial intelligence models.

196
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:58,000
 Therefore, the output per hour worked for an individual computer program has increased by 50% in a matter of one or two years, yeah.

197
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:03,000
 So this is, of course, just a small segment of the population, of the economically active population.

198
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:16,000
 But I think that we may be at the threshold, at the start of a new productivity cycle, which could also lead to, you know, labor savings in the years ahead.

199
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:18,000
 And it remains to be seen how this plays out.

200
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:32,000
 I mean, we can see that in the past, whenever there was a big increase in -- whenever there were big technological innovations, with a lag of two, three years, we've seen a trend increase in U.S. productivity growth.

201
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:39,000
 And we may be at, you know, at the start of another one of those eras, driven by artificial intelligence.

202
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:42,000
 And, you know, it remains to be seen how this will impact the labor market.

203
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:45,000
 And then, final question on what to do, yeah.

204
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:53,000
 So I don't have a quote here on that, but frankly, I think that the developments that we're seeing are extremely positive, no?

205
00:20:53,000 --> 00:21:02,000
 I mean, so we see a larger participation, especially of women in the labor force, yeah, driven by higher levels of education.

206
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:10,000
 And we have the chances, you know, all the opportunities that arise from the use of those technological innovations.

207
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:15,000
 Many of us have experienced that during the pandemic, that we can now work from home, yeah?

208
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:22,000
 I actually think that probably the productivity numbers which are published here underestimate the actual productivity growth.

209
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:27,000
 I mean, if I look at my office, yeah, people don't tend to work on Mondays and Fridays.

210
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:32,000
 They look at the computer from time to time, but they only come to the office three days a week.

211
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:34,000
 And they still get the same salary, yeah?

212
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:43,000
 So I actually think, you know, the number of hours worked has -- the effective number of hours worked in those office jobs has declined substantially, yeah?

213
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:47,000
 And that probably doesn't show up in the national accounts or in the statistics.

214
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:55,000
 So we may have just seen a massive increase in productivity through this working from home and teleconferencing and all that kind of stuff.

215
00:21:55,000 --> 00:22:06,000
 And I actually think that we're moving to a world which is, you know, pretty close to the world that Karl Marx has described in the German ideology,

216
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:21,000
 where in one famous paragraph he talks about communism as the status where you can be a hunter and a, you know, philosopher in the morning.

217
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:28,000
 You can be a hunter in the morning, you can be a philosopher in the afternoon, and you can do whatever else during the rest of the day.

218
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:31,000
 And you don't have to be confined to just one job, yeah?

219
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:39,000
 So I think that we're moving to a much more diverse, you know, working life and employment status,

220
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:43,000
 and one that will afford much greater liberties to most of us.

221
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:46,000
 So I think it's actually great development that lies ahead.

222
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:47,000
 Thank you.

223
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:48,000
 Thank you.

224
00:22:48,000 --> 00:23:17,980
 Hvala vam.

225
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:25,400
 Good morning. Let me start by thanking Boris and the National Bank of Croatia for inviting me again to this very interesting conference.

226
00:23:25,400 --> 00:23:34,760
 As a starter, I would also like to make two kavits. Not a customary institutional one, but more on substance.

227
00:23:34,760 --> 00:23:43,040
 One is that I'm not a labor economist. There are people in the room who are, so they are potentially better placed to look into this issue.

228
00:23:43,040 --> 00:23:47,180
 So I'm a macroeconomist and I look into the labor market from a macro perspective.

229
00:23:48,000 --> 00:24:03,220
 And second, I will talk essentially about the European labor market, which doesn't exist because the European labor market is a patchwork of around 50 clusters of regional labor markets.

230
00:24:03,380 --> 00:24:17,200
 So what I'm telling is very aggregated and generalized, but gives you some picture, but as already as the speaker has indicated, one has to look into country differences in order to be able to understand what's happening in the countries specifically.

231
00:24:19,260 --> 00:24:30,080
 In recent months, European policymakers has often and with a lot of praise referred to resilient labor markets.

232
00:24:30,920 --> 00:24:50,000
 The commissioner, when he presented the forecast on the 15th of May, also President Lagarde, on various occasions on the press conferences, was referring to resilient labor markets, which were welcome because they supported household spending and confidence.

233
00:24:51,680 --> 00:25:02,660
 In the same way, I shared that view, but I was always a little bit irritated because nobody was really defining what are you meaning by resilience, what are you measuring, what is the concept that you are using.

234
00:25:02,660 --> 00:25:14,180
 And so I will start very briefly, only two slides, and I will very quickly go over it, but just to place a little bit what is labor market resilience and what is not according to me.

235
00:25:14,680 --> 00:25:31,520
 Then I will look into a number of topical issues on the labor market, the employment situation after COVID, the personal coexistence of tightness and slack, and then wage developments, how they are, and then a number of concluding remarks.

236
00:25:31,520 --> 00:25:41,220
 On the concept of labor market resilience, in science, there is a very long history of the word resilience.

237
00:25:41,220 --> 00:25:56,180
 It is used very long and very detailed in physics and engineering and psychology, but it has, the term resilience has become fashionable by policy makers in Europe since Euro area crisis.

238
00:25:56,180 --> 00:26:07,700
 To some extent, in my view, it's worth otherwise than using flexibility or structural reforms, and so the resilience term, to some extent, was useful to that extent.

239
00:26:08,540 --> 00:26:22,700
 In economic terms, economic resilience refers to the ability of a country to withstand adverse shocks and to recover quickly to potential after adverse shocks.

240
00:26:22,700 --> 00:26:25,500
 That is the general definition of economic resilience.

241
00:26:25,500 --> 00:26:37,140
 Labor market resilience, on the contrary, I haven't found a shared definition or even a general shared understanding of what is meant by labor market resilience in the literature.

242
00:26:37,140 --> 00:26:38,140
 Again, I'm not a specialist.

243
00:26:38,140 --> 00:26:43,380
 I only have a week or two to look into that, but so if it exists, it's fine.

244
00:26:43,380 --> 00:26:47,380
 But the principle one can distinguish between two concepts.

245
00:26:47,380 --> 00:27:06,780
 One, which is very broad and is essentially due to the OECD, a seminal paper of 2014, where they have a very excellent paper, and where they defined the capacity, labor market resilience, as the capacity of the economy to limit persistent deviations from output and labor outcomes.

246
00:27:06,780 --> 00:27:11,180
 From pre-crisis trends and aftermath of adverse economic shocks.

247
00:27:11,180 --> 00:27:24,020
 That is a very broad definition, which I'm not very keen of, because you are mixing various elements, and in particular, you are mixing policies with labor market functioning.

248
00:27:24,020 --> 00:27:38,180
 And so I'm much more in favor of the more strict definition of resilience, which is the capacity of the labor market itself, independent of any policy support or withdrawal, to adapt and respond to economic shocks.

249
00:27:38,420 --> 00:27:45,220
 I come back to this at the very end, and I will also explain the title, somewhat provocative subtitle, of my presentation.

250
00:27:45,220 --> 00:27:54,260
 I will go very quickly over the next two slides, just a theoretical consideration on labor market resilience and how to define it and how to look into that.

251
00:27:54,260 --> 00:28:08,180
 From a political economy perspective, the extent to which the labor market is regulated and in the way it is managed influences the resilience of the economy.

252
00:28:08,180 --> 00:28:20,500
 And here, these slides present very simplistically and very generally, two types of labor market models, a competitive model and the cooperative model.

253
00:28:21,700 --> 00:28:34,180
 The competitive model argues that the institutional framework should formally and primarily be based on market principles of labor and supply.

254
00:28:34,180 --> 00:28:42,580
 And so this school of thought attaches a lot of importance to flexibility and deregulation of institutions, and certainly of the labor market.

255
00:28:42,580 --> 00:28:51,620
 The other concept is cooperative model, and it's much more on the way mechanisms are foreseen and required in the labor market,

256
00:28:51,620 --> 00:28:58,500
 to protect workers from structural inequalities in the relative power of the different shareholders in the market.

257
00:28:58,500 --> 00:29:01,620
 I will not go into the details and further explanations of that.

258
00:29:01,620 --> 00:29:04,340
 I'm happy to do that overrange with those who are interested.

259
00:29:04,340 --> 00:29:13,700
 There is an ongoing, very rich debate academically and politically on these two concepts, and to what extent one has more merits than the other.

260
00:29:13,700 --> 00:29:15,620
 But that is not the purpose of the discussion today.

261
00:29:15,620 --> 00:29:21,540
 What is important from this discussion is that, in principle, you need to take the two schools of thoughts.

262
00:29:21,540 --> 00:29:26,420
 What they say, and then look into the variables that determine labor market resilience.

263
00:29:26,420 --> 00:29:33,300
 And so here, this table, schematically, gives you three indications.

264
00:29:33,300 --> 00:29:37,220
 Institutional structure, socioeconomic structure, and demographic context.

265
00:29:37,220 --> 00:29:43,940
 All of these variables, in principle, have one way or another a bearing on the resilience of the labor market.

266
00:29:44,900 --> 00:29:46,660
 I will not go into the details here.

267
00:29:46,660 --> 00:29:59,620
 Very, very roughly, I could say that the first category in the last couple of, over the last decade, there has been quite a number of improvements in the institutional structure in European countries.

268
00:29:59,620 --> 00:30:11,380
 So, which would suggest to have some improved resilience, and that's certainly true in the crisis countries, where there has been quite a lot of labor market reforms, to a lesser extent in other countries.

269
00:30:11,380 --> 00:30:18,820
 While on the other two factors, socioeconomic and demographic factors, the outcome is more mixed, and you have improvements and deteriorations.

270
00:30:18,820 --> 00:30:23,700
 So, just this to put a little bit in the framework of resilience.

271
00:30:23,700 --> 00:30:27,780
 Let me now move to a number of developments in the labor market in the EU.

272
00:30:27,780 --> 00:30:31,540
 And the first one is developments in employment.

273
00:30:32,260 --> 00:30:40,820
 The left handslide is employment and unemployment in millions, so it's not in percentages, it's in millions.

274
00:30:40,820 --> 00:30:56,420
 And the graphs indicate that after the widespread job retention schemes that shielded workers from a pronounced slowdown in 2020, the labor market rebounds quite strongly after the pandemic.

275
00:30:57,060 --> 00:31:05,860
 It also indicates that despite the weakening of economic activity towards the end of 2021, unemployment again rebounded.

276
00:31:05,860 --> 00:31:09,460
 The same is true for unemployment.

277
00:31:09,460 --> 00:31:16,020
 You can see that employment slightly increased, but not that much, and then rapidly came down.

278
00:31:16,020 --> 00:31:24,260
 That development in the labor market over the last couple of years is quite different from the period after the 2008 crisis,

279
00:31:24,260 --> 00:31:31,300
 where it took six years in order to achieve employment and unemployment levels of before the crisis.

280
00:31:31,300 --> 00:31:38,180
 And here, already in late 2022, we achieved again the levels of employment and unemployment that we had.

281
00:31:38,180 --> 00:31:40,500
 So, that's the positive picture.

282
00:31:40,500 --> 00:31:47,300
 The somewhat less positive picture is indicated with a dotted line, and the dotted line gives the

283
00:31:48,100 --> 00:31:58,020
 trend increase in employment and unemployment, the trend over 2013-2018, and what if that would have been continued without the pandemic.

284
00:31:58,020 --> 00:32:08,340
 And there you can see that in terms of employment, we are still around 3 million of persons employed less than the trend would have suggested.

285
00:32:08,340 --> 00:32:14,340
 So, we have not yet fully recovered from the pandemic, and also unemployment has not yet fully recovered.

286
00:32:14,340 --> 00:32:23,700
 It has come down to 6%, but has not recovered to and still 1.6 million more than the trend would have suggested without the pandemic.

287
00:32:23,700 --> 00:32:27,940
 So, from that perspective, it's positive.

288
00:32:27,940 --> 00:32:34,980
 It's also positive that we no longer have this ratcheting effect of unemployment, that after every crisis, unemployment gets higher.

289
00:32:34,980 --> 00:32:37,060
 That was in the '80s and the '90s the case.

290
00:32:37,060 --> 00:32:41,940
 So, from that perspective, we have seen quite a more resilient labor market than we have seen before.

291
00:32:42,500 --> 00:32:53,700
 Let's move to the vacancy rates, and here the graph you can indicate, you can see that despite the slowdown, we have a very strong increase in vacancy rates over the last couple of years.

292
00:32:53,700 --> 00:33:10,820
 There has been a very slow and small reduction at the end of 2022, and from that perspective, we can see that a high vacancy rate can act as a buffer for unemployment in terms of, over in times of economic crisis.

293
00:33:10,820 --> 00:33:19,140
 This questioning effect from vacancies only functions to the extent that the labor market works efficiently.

294
00:33:19,140 --> 00:33:24,500
 If that is not the case, then you will not have this dampening effect from vacancies on unemployment.

295
00:33:24,500 --> 00:33:39,460
 Already, the chair has referred to the beverage curve, and that's the standard model or the standard concept to look into

296
00:33:40,820 --> 00:33:45,460
 the efficiency and the degree of mid-smatch in the labor market.

297
00:33:45,460 --> 00:33:52,740
 So, the labor, the beverage curve, the relationship between unemployment and vacancies, or labor shortages.

298
00:33:52,740 --> 00:33:55,300
 Here is labor shortages, but that's the same as vacancy rate.

299
00:33:55,300 --> 00:34:04,420
 And what we can see here is that over, during the previous crisis, these are the blue dotted lines,

300
00:34:04,500 --> 00:34:10,980
 we got an outward shift in the beverage curve, which means that it was deterioration in the match on the labor market.

301
00:34:10,980 --> 00:34:20,340
 Now, in the latest couple of years, which are the gray dots, and it's somewhat shown by the green line,

302
00:34:20,340 --> 00:34:25,940
 we can see that there is no outward movement of the of the beverage curve during the last couple of years.

303
00:34:25,940 --> 00:34:33,060
 So, which is indicative that there has been no structural mismatch over the last couple of years in the European labor market.

304
00:34:33,060 --> 00:34:38,900
 If there were, if there would have been a deterioration, then we would have followed the upper blue line.

305
00:34:38,900 --> 00:34:46,260
 That would have been the beverage curve in terms of mismatches or important mismatches in the labor market.

306
00:34:46,260 --> 00:34:56,980
 So, again, that's a positive development that we have seen, but again, we have high vacancy ratios with an unemployment rate of still around 6%.

307
00:34:56,980 --> 00:35:01,700
 So, which is suggestive of, nevertheless, some structural problems in the labor market.

308
00:35:01,700 --> 00:35:07,300
 Let's move to wages, and also previous speakers have already referred to wages.

309
00:35:07,300 --> 00:35:13,140
 So, here we can see different measures of wages over the cycle.

310
00:35:13,140 --> 00:35:15,460
 Two graphs are from the ECB.

311
00:35:16,260 --> 00:35:22,100
 The most interesting one is on the right hand side, which gives the dryness of wage growth in the Euro area.

312
00:35:22,100 --> 00:35:29,700
 And the graph shows deviations from a model implied trend.

313
00:35:29,700 --> 00:35:37,860
 So, what you see here, the blue line is a wage compensation per head, and you can see that it is below what the model would have suggested.

314
00:35:37,860 --> 00:35:42,420
 So, wage growth has been sluggish compared to what the model would have suggested.

315
00:35:43,060 --> 00:35:49,620
 And then the model is used to look into the determinants of this slugginess in wage growth.

316
00:35:49,620 --> 00:35:57,140
 And here, three factors are important.

317
00:35:57,140 --> 00:36:01,300
 And you can see that the blue column was very important during the period 2013 to 2016.

318
00:36:01,300 --> 00:36:10,740
 So, during that period, labor slack in the European Union affected a negative impact on wage developments in Europe.

319
00:36:11,460 --> 00:36:23,060
 The second element is past inflation, which is the red bar, and here you can see that past inflation became an important driver as of 2016.

320
00:36:23,700 --> 00:36:36,340
 And going further, up to 2018, it stops, but you can see that it was a very important driver of the last couple of years, although it dissipated with the impact in the latter years.

321
00:36:36,340 --> 00:36:41,060
 We'll come back later on at the end to what it would imply for the current situation.

322
00:36:41,060 --> 00:36:52,180
 And then you have productivity growth, and there you can see that productivity growth has only had a very minor impact on wage developments in the European Union.

323
00:36:53,620 --> 00:37:04,580
 So, what does this mean, this wage developments for European labor share?

324
00:37:06,260 --> 00:37:29,620
 Because on top of low productivity growth, low inflation, and substantial labor markets lag, there is strong empirical literature which indicates that technological advance and internationalization of goods and services is also impacting on wage development and on the labor share.

325
00:37:30,020 --> 00:37:37,540
 The labor share is an issue which has been discussed for potentially two centuries, starting with both this law, so I will not go that long.

326
00:37:37,540 --> 00:37:57,380
 But interesting here to see is that I don't have the full graph because the data are not available for all the countries, but we can see that from the 1970s onwards, 1980s onwards, for all advanced economies, European and US, the labor share was on a declining trend up to around the turn of the century.

327
00:37:57,860 --> 00:38:09,460
 And since then, we have seen a quite stable labor share, with some variation according to the cycle, but we had a quite low, stable and low weight share in Europe.

328
00:38:09,460 --> 00:38:24,060
 I only for, out of courtesy for the guest, I only put Croatia on the graph, and you can see that for Croatia, it's typically for a less developed country, which is later than the other countries.

329
00:38:24,060 --> 00:38:31,420
 It's labor share, its labor share started still, and was on a very high level, at around 80%, but is now coming down very quickly.

330
00:38:31,420 --> 00:38:34,140
 So, let me conclude.

331
00:38:34,140 --> 00:38:38,060
 So, let me conclude somewhat atypically with four questions.

332
00:38:38,060 --> 00:38:41,100
 Labor market resilience, boon or bane?

333
00:38:41,100 --> 00:38:51,660
 So, of course, the labor market, if it is resilience, it has to be welcomed, because it means that the labor market is adjusting to economic shocks.

334
00:38:51,660 --> 00:39:15,180
 Where I'm a little bit more skeptical is that the extent to which that resilience is temporary, or is due to policy measures, like very extensive job retention schemes, or temporary work, that could, not say it will, but that could lead to a kind of blockage of reallocation of labor.

335
00:39:15,180 --> 00:39:28,380
 And so, from that perspective, it's good if it is very short-term and targeted, if it is widespread and long, then I'm much less convinced that that type of resilience is good for the economy.

336
00:39:28,380 --> 00:39:37,180
 Of course, it is also good to avoid scarring effects on the labor market, that's true, but again, reallocation of labor is very important.

337
00:39:37,180 --> 00:39:47,980
 Second one, labor market tightness or slack, that is a very difficult question, and in my view, it's too early to say that what we have seen is temporary, or it could be permanent.

338
00:39:47,980 --> 00:40:04,180
 I would not be surprised that it is permanent, so that's my own take, I don't have a very strong theoretical or empirical basis for that, but if I look on what's happening in the labor market, I do see quite a lot of mismatches in demand and supply in the European labor market.

339
00:40:04,180 --> 00:40:14,980
 These structural problems in the labor market were already there pre-pandemic, so that is often forgotten, but many structural problems in European labor markets were there.

340
00:40:14,980 --> 00:40:29,300
 They were somewhat hidden during the crisis with all kinds of measures and temporary support, but when these things are fading out, the structural problems resurfaces, and there we can see that we have real problems, certainly on the labor supply.

341
00:40:29,300 --> 00:40:45,300
 And here, there are, for the policy conclusions, there are two elements, one is to improve skills, if you want to increase the labor supply, there is certainly a need to improve the skills, it's a little bit the same as Christian is saying, my education level, so that's a little bit the same story.

342
00:40:45,300 --> 00:41:00,100
 We really have to invest much more in training, education, active labor market policies in order to get people back into the labor market with the required skills, so that's certainly an issue which has been underdeveloped recently.

343
00:41:00,100 --> 00:41:24,100
 And third, and secondly, one has to increase the supply of labor itself, by bringing those who are not active in the labor market, again referred to by women, I'm a little bit less positive than Christian, there is still quite a cohort of the labor force for women, which can be used, and so it's too small, and we really have to look into immigration as well.

344
00:41:24,100 --> 00:41:38,100
 That's not an issue, not discussed by the chair neither, but immigration, not only from Eastern Europe, but immigration from outside Europe, in order to fill, importantly, low-skilled jobs, where the price and the wages are up, is very important.

345
00:41:38,100 --> 00:41:50,100
 Last point, because the chair is putting some signals to me, we moved from wage inertia, to concern about wage price developments.

346
00:41:50,100 --> 00:42:00,100
 Wage inertia was very strong over the last decade after the crisis, and I have seen papers saying that wage inertia is a bad thing and should be activated.

347
00:42:00,100 --> 00:42:11,100
 Part of it was a problem with Germany and the current account surplus, and so it was a normative approach to say that wages should increase in order to reduce the current account surplus in Germany.

348
00:42:11,100 --> 00:42:15,100
 But that fear of inertia has gone now to wage price spiral.

349
00:42:15,100 --> 00:42:17,100
 Three elements, and then I conclude here.

350
00:42:17,100 --> 00:42:25,100
 One is, as we have indicated, and in the graph, past inflation is a very important driver of wages.

351
00:42:25,100 --> 00:42:37,100
 And so from that perspective, to the extent that policymakers succeed in anchoring price expectations at a low level, that element for the wage curve would not be affected that much.

352
00:42:37,100 --> 00:42:44,100
 I'm not sure that it will be the case, because it's not only expectations, it's also actual inflation.

353
00:42:44,100 --> 00:42:51,100
 And if that actual inflation remains of four or five percent, that will feed into the wage of the people.

354
00:42:51,100 --> 00:42:57,100
 The second one is the labour market tightness, and so there as well I'm perhaps a little bit more sceptical than others.

355
00:42:57,100 --> 00:43:05,100
 I do think that labour market tightness is a structural issue, and that it will also fuel wage developments in Europe.

356
00:43:05,100 --> 00:43:10,100
 And so from that perspective, I do think that wages can surprise on the positive side.

357
00:43:10,100 --> 00:43:14,100
 And the third element, which was discussed very much yesterday, is the profit margins.

358
00:43:14,100 --> 00:43:20,100
 And I share the view that profit margins can act as a buffer for wage increases for the time being.

359
00:43:20,100 --> 00:43:27,100
 But from a political economy perspective, there is a renewed income distribution struggle potentially before us.

360
00:43:27,100 --> 00:43:38,100
 And so from that perspective, if the profit share is so high, that is an invitation for employees, for trade unions, to ask much higher wage increases than they have seen so far.

361
00:43:38,100 --> 00:43:42,100
 And that will not be for one year, but that will be for a couple of years coupled with a tight labour market.

362
00:43:42,100 --> 00:43:48,100
 I'm sorry if I was too long.

363
00:43:48,100 --> 00:43:49,100
 Thank you very much, Savas.

364
00:43:49,100 --> 00:43:53,100
 Now we'll turn to Vedran Sosic of the Croatian National Bike.

365
00:43:53,100 --> 00:43:55,100
 Thank you, Jeff.

366
00:43:55,100 --> 00:44:03,100
 So, Governor yesterday said that this started as a conference on transition economies and then became a general economic conference,

367
00:44:03,100 --> 00:44:11,100
 but we could have adjusted the title over the time because we had a period when this was a conference on global financial crisis.

368
00:44:11,100 --> 00:44:16,100
 For the past couple of years, this was a conference on pandemic economy.

369
00:44:16,100 --> 00:44:19,100
 And now I see that we have moved into the post-pandemic economy.

370
00:44:19,100 --> 00:44:23,100
 So we are looking in this new post-pandemic world for a new overarching theme.

371
00:44:23,100 --> 00:44:34,100
 And in this new post-pandemic world, labour market is definitely one of the important topics that is a cross-cutting theme for a number of issues.

372
00:44:34,100 --> 00:44:46,100
 Much has been said yesterday, also today, so it's not easy to add anything, but it's interesting because two days ago when I arrived,

373
00:44:46,100 --> 00:44:53,100
 Radovan said something like we never had more people on Earth, we never had more robots and more automation, more technology,

374
00:44:53,100 --> 00:44:55,100
 and the demand for labour has never been greater.

375
00:44:55,100 --> 00:44:59,100
 So that's something I can call Radovan Conundrum.

376
00:44:59,100 --> 00:45:04,100
 And this panel is, I guess, about Radovan Conundrum.

377
00:45:04,100 --> 00:45:08,100
 So, the exceptional resilience of the labour market.

378
00:45:08,100 --> 00:45:12,100
 In part, this is definitely a result of the robust economy.

379
00:45:12,100 --> 00:45:23,100
 You know, I was here during the pandemic, and by the way, I probably earned a lifetime post in panel for the hard work I put in during the pandemic.

380
00:45:23,100 --> 00:45:31,100
 But I remember last year we discussed that recession is six months away, so we were expecting recession.

381
00:45:31,100 --> 00:45:36,100
 And the recession is still six months away, a year later.

382
00:45:36,100 --> 00:45:39,100
 And you will see that some people call this Godot recession.

383
00:45:39,100 --> 00:45:45,100
 So when it comes, it will probably be remembered as Godot recession, the most expected recession ever.

384
00:45:45,100 --> 00:45:51,100
 So the economy is still doing quite good, and which is also good for labour market.

385
00:45:51,100 --> 00:45:59,100
 But it is more than just the economy, there is more to the strength of the economy.

386
00:45:59,100 --> 00:46:08,100
 And the series of beverage curve started yesterday with Mr. De La Riccia, who's first mentioned, and Jeff Servaz.

387
00:46:08,100 --> 00:46:17,100
 So you will hear a lot about this beverage curve, the schedule showing relationship between vacancies and unemployment.

388
00:46:17,100 --> 00:46:20,100
 And indeed, the number of vacancies shot up.

389
00:46:20,100 --> 00:46:30,100
 So this resilience, I guess, for me, it's very low unemployment in combination with exceptionally high number of vacancies.

390
00:46:30,100 --> 00:46:39,100
 And actually, the upward move in beverage curve, it is a sign of less efficient matching in the labour market.

391
00:46:39,100 --> 00:46:42,100
 So the labour market became less efficient.

392
00:46:42,100 --> 00:46:53,100
 But on the other hand, it opens up hope that the reduction in vacancies will not be followed by increasing unemployment,

393
00:46:53,100 --> 00:46:57,100
 but rather improved matching in the labour market.

394
00:46:57,100 --> 00:47:10,100
 So that's one important thing.

395
00:47:10,100 --> 00:47:16,100
 The one thing that has not been touched much upon, and I would like to point it out, is the shape of the recovery.

396
00:47:16,100 --> 00:47:17,100
 Some people mentioned.

397
00:47:17,100 --> 00:47:21,100
 We had a very uneven recovery.

398
00:47:21,100 --> 00:47:26,100
 We had a divergence between the different economic sectors, between activities.

399
00:47:26,100 --> 00:47:29,100
 And the recovery was particularly strong in services.

400
00:47:29,100 --> 00:47:36,100
 And in services, typically these are labour-intensive activities, particularly contact-intensive services.

401
00:47:36,100 --> 00:47:38,100
 You cannot do much automation there.

402
00:47:38,100 --> 00:47:40,100
 So it really relies on labour.

403
00:47:40,100 --> 00:47:49,100
 So this is probably also one of the reasons why the labour market has been so resilient.

404
00:47:49,100 --> 00:47:59,100
 So we know, we have anecdotal evidence about all this skinflation, the reduction in the quality of service.

405
00:47:59,100 --> 00:48:04,100
 A hotel can maybe skip making room for a day, but not for two or three days.

406
00:48:04,100 --> 00:48:10,100
 So there is limit how much services can spare, optimize labour.

407
00:48:10,100 --> 00:48:15,100
 And also, labour market, we have to keep in mind that labour market is a lagging indicator.

408
00:48:15,100 --> 00:48:23,100
 So, you know, when the recession, this Godot recession eventually comes, labour market will be the last to know that there is a recession.

409
00:48:23,100 --> 00:48:27,100
 It will wake up six months later and realize that something happened.

410
00:48:27,100 --> 00:48:31,100
 Also, labour share, a lot has been discussed.

411
00:48:31,100 --> 00:48:47,100
 One theory is that employers now don't want, they hoard labour because they are afraid of, when they lose employees, that they will not be able to find other new employees if and when demand increases.

412
00:48:47,100 --> 00:48:50,100
 I suspect this is not entirely true.

413
00:48:50,100 --> 00:48:55,100
 The robust demand is probably more to wage development.

414
00:48:55,100 --> 00:49:00,100
 So we have seen increasing the inflation, declining labour shares.

415
00:49:00,100 --> 00:49:05,100
 It became cheaper for employers to keep labour.

416
00:49:05,100 --> 00:49:06,100
 Labour is cheap.

417
00:49:06,100 --> 00:49:10,100
 So that's probably an important reason behind this hoarding.

418
00:49:10,100 --> 00:49:14,100
 This type of inflation was not the same everywhere.

419
00:49:14,100 --> 00:49:21,100
 It was particularly present in Central and Eastern European countries.

420
00:49:21,100 --> 00:49:28,100
 In core Europe, profits probably did not increase as much according to the data we have.

421
00:49:28,100 --> 00:49:37,100
 So this is probably one of the reasons also for particular strength of the labour markets in Central and Eastern Europe.

422
00:49:37,100 --> 00:49:41,100
 And finally, demography.

423
00:49:41,100 --> 00:49:42,100
 We heard about the demography.

424
00:49:42,100 --> 00:49:46,100
 We heard about the demography, but it is really starting to bite.

425
00:49:46,100 --> 00:49:47,100
 Demography.

426
00:49:47,100 --> 00:49:53,100
 The remarkable thing about the EU is that the population growth came to a halt a few years ago.

427
00:49:53,100 --> 00:50:01,100
 So during the pandemic, population in EU did not increase, but it got older.

428
00:50:01,100 --> 00:50:06,100
 So there was a reduction in immigration and population.

429
00:50:06,100 --> 00:50:12,100
 So it was at about 446, 47 million in 2022.

430
00:50:12,100 --> 00:50:14,100
 And it was stable for three years.

431
00:50:14,100 --> 00:50:22,100
 Previously, migration compensated or compensated for natural decline of the population.

432
00:50:22,100 --> 00:50:34,100
 But during the pandemic, this source of population increase started to dry up.

433
00:50:34,100 --> 00:50:43,100
 And the labour force, if you look at the EU labour force declined for the past 10 years by about 5 million.

434
00:50:43,100 --> 00:50:56,100
 So with the population becoming older, there is less people that can enter the labour force.

435
00:50:56,100 --> 00:50:59,100
 And in CE countries, it's even worse.

436
00:50:59,100 --> 00:51:00,100
 We saw the numbers.

437
00:51:00,100 --> 00:51:03,100
 I accept a few exceptions.

438
00:51:03,100 --> 00:51:04,100
 Slovenia, Czech Republic.

439
00:51:04,100 --> 00:51:07,100
 There was a strong emigration from CE countries.

440
00:51:07,100 --> 00:51:10,100
 So their population decline was much stronger.

441
00:51:10,100 --> 00:51:14,100
 And they got old before they got rich.

442
00:51:14,100 --> 00:51:19,100
 So which is also compounding, compounding the problem.

443
00:51:19,100 --> 00:51:22,100
 And where do we go from here?

444
00:51:22,100 --> 00:51:28,100
 Probably there will be not a major, major change in the labour market.

445
00:51:28,100 --> 00:51:33,100
 No one expects that stagnation or maybe slight increase in unemployment.

446
00:51:33,100 --> 00:51:38,100
 That's for all the institutions, the IMF, the ECB, the Commission foresees.

447
00:51:38,100 --> 00:51:48,100
 For central banks, it's also very important.

448
00:51:48,100 --> 00:51:53,100
 What we see, we see immaculate this inflation.

449
00:51:53,100 --> 00:51:58,100
 So we see a gradual catch up of wages, real wage growth.

450
00:51:58,100 --> 00:51:59,100
 And it's already happening.

451
00:51:59,100 --> 00:52:06,100
 I mean, in Croatia, Slovenia, real wages already made up much of the ground lost during the pandemic.

452
00:52:06,100 --> 00:52:23,100
 And this is also, so we rely on this downward shift, the gradual reduction, gradual improvement in matching and the reduction in the share of profits and increasing labour share.

453
00:52:23,100 --> 00:52:24,100
 But there is a risk.

454
00:52:24,100 --> 00:52:28,100
 What if wage growth turns into a spiral?

455
00:52:28,100 --> 00:52:40,100
 What if employers decide that they would like to keep their profits, high profits, the level of reach during the, during the, in the aftermath of the pandemic?

456
00:52:40,100 --> 00:52:43,100
 So, so there is obviously a risk there.

457
00:52:43,100 --> 00:52:53,100
 So all, all, all forecasts rely on a set of, on assumptions that, that is not, that is not given.

458
00:52:53,100 --> 00:52:55,100
 Policies, maybe we can leave this further.

459
00:52:55,100 --> 00:52:56,100
 I don't know if I'm over time.

460
00:52:56,100 --> 00:52:57,100
 One more minute.

461
00:52:57,100 --> 00:52:58,100
 One more minute.

462
00:52:58,100 --> 00:52:59,100
 One more minute.

463
00:52:59,100 --> 00:53:01,100
 So policies, we heard about participation.

464
00:53:01,100 --> 00:53:04,100
 It was actually quite good in increasing participation rate.

465
00:53:04,100 --> 00:53:12,100
 It compensated for much of, of the, it's overcompensated for, for the declining.

466
00:53:12,100 --> 00:53:16,100
 Actually Christian showed the participation rate until, for those under 50.

467
00:53:16,100 --> 00:53:20,100
 And it actually increased a lot for those over 50.

468
00:53:20,100 --> 00:53:31,100
 With employers, we see automation, which is more probably better, better, greater opportunities are in service, in industry-based economies than in service-based industries.

469
00:53:31,100 --> 00:53:33,100
 Education and upgrading of skills.

470
00:53:33,100 --> 00:53:35,100
 But this is, this is complicated.

471
00:53:35,100 --> 00:53:48,100
 that service show that you need to embed your education and skilling policies into a specific set of labor market policies, social policies.

472
00:53:48,100 --> 00:53:50,100
 So you cannot work on that in isolation.

473
00:53:50,100 --> 00:53:58,100
 It really needs to be adapted to, to specific, to specific circumstances.

474
00:53:58,100 --> 00:54:03,100
 Finally, immigration, we heard a lot about that yesterday.

475
00:54:03,100 --> 00:54:09,100
 So this is new, because in Croatia we had a lot of immigration before, but that was from neighboring countries.

476
00:54:09,100 --> 00:54:15,100
 And now these neighboring countries dried up and we are seeking immigrants further and further away.

477
00:54:15,100 --> 00:54:16,100
 So it will be an interesting challenge.

478
00:54:16,100 --> 00:54:17,100
 Thank you.

479
00:54:17,100 --> 00:54:18,100
 Okay.

480
00:54:18,100 --> 00:54:19,100
 Thank you very much.

481
00:54:19,100 --> 00:54:26,100
 Okay, now Tina Zumer of the Slovenian National Bike.

482
00:54:26,100 --> 00:54:27,100
 Okay.

483
00:54:27,100 --> 00:54:28,100
 Thank you very much.

484
00:54:28,100 --> 00:54:29,100
 Thank you.

485
00:54:29,100 --> 00:54:33,100
 Thanks the organizers for inviting me.

486
00:54:33,100 --> 00:54:38,100
 Again, last year I was on a panel talking about inflation.

487
00:54:38,100 --> 00:54:45,100
 This year it's about labor markets, which is, I would say, quite unusual topic in a sense for us policymakers.

488
00:54:45,100 --> 00:54:50,100
 But indeed it's at the heart of our thinking currently.

489
00:54:50,100 --> 00:55:01,100
 I will focus mainly on our own Slovenian perspective, also being part of the, let's say, Euro area, but also part of the region.

490
00:55:01,100 --> 00:55:09,100
 So I think much has been heard already, but I hope I will add some new insights on that.

491
00:55:09,100 --> 00:55:25,100
 So when talking about labor markets, of course, for us the key risk going ahead is labor shortages to actually ensure adequate labor supply, not to be impediment for growth going ahead.

492
00:55:25,100 --> 00:55:30,100
 So this is one of our major downside risks for the growth outlook.

493
00:55:30,100 --> 00:55:35,100
 And on the other hand, high wage growth being the major upside risk to the inflation outlook.

494
00:55:35,100 --> 00:55:38,100
 So quite unfavorable metrics.

495
00:55:38,100 --> 00:55:55,100
 And if I say like the main characteristics of the labor market would be that the structure trends that we observed before the pandemic still continue also after the pandemic.

496
00:55:55,100 --> 00:56:12,100
 So, and on the other hand, what we saw that this pandemic effect was very short lived and very well absorbed thanks to the large policy stimulus, which we should not forget.

497
00:56:12,100 --> 00:56:25,100
 And also maybe better than we thought and expected flexibility and the capacity of the adapt to adapt to such shocks of our economy.

498
00:56:25,100 --> 00:56:41,100
 So in that respect, I think we would, we would fit to serve us resilience definition, let's say in our Slovenian labor markets, which actually now stand at really historical numbers, historical low unemployment of 3.5%, which is much better.

499
00:56:41,100 --> 00:56:48,100
 And the estimates of Naira historical employment and high historically high vacancy rates.

500
00:56:48,100 --> 00:57:10,100
 Two features maybe that I would want to point out that we observed post pandemic is a somewhat more rigidity of the labor market labor hoarding what we heard in despite labor markets firms seem to prefer to retain labor for a bit longer.

501
00:57:10,100 --> 00:57:11,100
 So we will see what it means going ahead.

502
00:57:11,100 --> 00:57:17,100
 So we will see what it means going ahead.

503
00:57:17,100 --> 00:57:21,100
 Explaining to some extent, of course, this resilience that we are observing.

504
00:57:21,100 --> 00:57:32,100
 And on the other hand, what we observe is more wage bargaining power and this is seen in very high wage growth on the one hand and much more collective agreements.

505
00:57:32,100 --> 00:57:33,100
 So they became alive again.

506
00:57:33,100 --> 00:57:44,100
 In Slovenia, just to give you a flavor, minimum wage growth increased by 12% and it's very much binding.

507
00:57:44,100 --> 00:57:50,100
 So we have a high wage compression due to such wage, minimum wage increases.

508
00:57:51,100 --> 00:57:56,100
 And so maybe let me turn to the outlook.

509
00:57:56,100 --> 00:58:10,100
 So overall on the structural front, I think that the structural challenges that we have been observing now for a decade since the European crisis will persist and will stay with us for some time.

510
00:58:10,100 --> 00:58:28,100
 On the other hand, to the more short term outlook, so we see some moderation in the employment expectations, but we still see strong wage growth in nominal terms coming.

511
00:58:28,100 --> 00:58:35,100
 So this is also due to the indexation, backward indexation that is prevailing, either formal or non-formal.

512
00:58:35,100 --> 00:58:40,100
 People still want to catch up for the loss in the purchasing power.

513
00:58:40,100 --> 00:58:47,100
 And that will also result in the real wage growth, partly reflecting some catch up.

514
00:58:47,100 --> 00:58:57,100
 But as Vedran said, also in Slovenia, actually the real wage growth have already recovered from the pre-pandemic levels.

515
00:58:57,100 --> 00:59:06,100
 And one should not or could not talk about this without touching about profit margins.

516
00:59:06,100 --> 00:59:15,100
 Also in Slovenia, we saw quite some profit margins that we believe would serve as a buffer during our projection horizon.

517
00:59:15,100 --> 00:59:22,100
 So therefore, we don't see the full pass on of this real wage increases to the prices.

518
00:59:22,100 --> 00:59:31,100
 To conclude with the more medium term challenges, yes, as I said at the beginning, I think it's really touching upon the labor supply.

519
00:59:31,100 --> 00:59:40,100
 And this will also have, of course, implication for our medium term inflation outlook, R-STAR and all these structure issues that will stay with us.

520
00:59:40,100 --> 00:59:47,100
 And here is really to provide for policies, then I will not go into the policy discussion.

521
00:59:47,100 --> 00:59:53,100
 I think they are self-evident and sort of us, I think, also nicely summarized them.

522
00:59:53,100 --> 01:00:03,100
 But it's really to supply enough adequate, to supply enough and adequate and productivity enhancing labor supply.

523
01:00:03,100 --> 01:00:12,100
 So working age population is expected to decrease significantly in Slovenia and that despite the immigration projections.

524
01:00:12,100 --> 01:00:15,100
 So we will need to leave with some immigration over the time.

525
01:00:15,100 --> 01:00:18,100
 But nevertheless, the projections don't look good.

526
01:00:18,100 --> 01:00:25,100
 So here it's key to increase the participation of the young and elderly.

527
01:00:25,100 --> 01:00:35,100
 So there are special schemes that prevent those groups to enter the labor, not prevent, but prevent incentives to enter the labor market.

528
01:00:35,100 --> 01:00:41,100
 So in Slovenia, let's say the young cohort, its participation rate is only 30%.

529
01:00:41,100 --> 01:00:50,100
 The good news that the elderly have started to increase, to enter the labor market again, but there is, of course, further scope.

530
01:00:50,100 --> 01:01:00,100
 Because we should bear in mind that in our region, the exit rate, it's among, also in Slovenia, among the lowest in the OECD countries.

531
01:01:00,100 --> 01:01:05,100
 That is from the legacy perspective.

532
01:01:05,100 --> 01:01:11,100
 So furthermore, relying on the immigrants or, let's say, foreign workers.

533
01:01:11,100 --> 01:01:17,100
 Currently, in Slovenia, 80% of the newly hired are coming from abroad.

534
01:01:17,100 --> 01:01:21,100
 I think they're representing about 6% of the employed people currently.

535
01:01:21,100 --> 01:01:27,100
 There are mostly low-skilled, low-paid workers.

536
01:01:27,100 --> 01:01:30,100
 So another avenue, adequate workforce.

537
01:01:30,100 --> 01:01:39,100
 I think here it's very important not to forget the green and digital transformation, which is hindered by the missing skills.

538
01:01:39,100 --> 01:01:54,100
 And one could see that by a very high vacancy ratio, a vacancy share in the shortages reported in the ICT services, electrical equipment,

539
01:01:54,100 --> 01:02:02,100
 which are key for this transformation and these shortages among, in Slovenia, among the highest in the EU, as well as in construction.

540
01:02:02,100 --> 01:02:17,100
 And in this respect, I think it's also important to bear in mind, for instance, that in Slovenia we have very high energy intensive industry employment,

541
01:02:17,100 --> 01:02:22,100
 higher than the average of the Euro area, and also higher share of manufacturing.

542
01:02:22,100 --> 01:02:31,100
 So this all calls for, let's say, reskilling, upskilling, for re-education.

543
01:02:31,100 --> 01:02:38,100
 And then finally, productivity, upskilling, it will be key because I think we all want our wages to grow.

544
01:02:38,100 --> 01:02:40,100
 We want to catch up.

545
01:02:40,100 --> 01:02:48,100
 But, of course, only with higher productivity growth and here the scores for Slovenia innovation are just medium.

546
01:02:48,100 --> 01:02:50,100
 So I think there is scope again here and here.

547
01:02:50,100 --> 01:02:54,100
 I think we can go to the policy discussion later on, which I will skip.

548
01:02:54,100 --> 01:02:56,100
 Thank you very much for your attention.

